I created a new thread simply using:

```cs
Thread thread = new Thread(Execute);
thread.Start(cancellationToken);
```

where the `Execute` method is as defined as:

```cs
private void Execute(object data)
{
	CancellationToken cancellationToken = (CancellationToken)data;

	while (_run && !cancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested)
	{
		_logger.LogInformation($"{nameof(ServiceMonitor)}: Create process for {Path.GetFileName(_appSettings.Service)}.");
		_logger.LogInformation($"{nameof(ServiceMonitor)}: Current directory: {Environment.CurrentDirectory}");

		using (_process = new Process())
		{
			try
			{
				_processDisposed = false;
				_process.Disposed += Process_Disposed;

				_process.StartInfo.FileName = _appSettings.Service;
				_process.StartInfo.Arguments = _appSettings.Arguments;

				_process.StartInfo.UseShellExecute = false;
				_process.StartInfo.CreateNoWindow = true;
				_process.Start();

				_logger.LogInformation($"{nameof(ServiceMonitor)}({_appSettings.ServiceName}): - Process started");

				_process.WaitForExit();
			}
			catch (Exception ex)
			{
				_logger.LogError(ex, $"Task.Run #00");
			}
		}

		_process = null;

		throw new Exception("We have failed!");

		_logger.LogInformation($"{nameof(ServiceMonitor)}({_appSettings.ServiceName}): - Process stopped");

		if (_run && !cancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested)
		{
			Thread.Sleep(_appSettings.RestartDelay * 1000);
		}
	}
}
```

When the exception occurs within the `using` statement, the line number is correctly reported.  However, anywhere else within the `while` statement, the StackTrace will show the line number of the `while` statement, and not the actual line number of where the exception occurred.

I haven't tried under different circumstances, as I'm under a time crunch and only have enough time to report the bug, and it's not preventing me from moving forward.

When the Diagnostics Server receives a Collect Tracing command, it will eventually call `EventPipe::Enable(...)`.  `Enable` is in charge of creating the session, initializing buffer flushing, initializing the file format, and sending the IPC response.  

Currently, The IPC response is sent in the constructor for `IpcStreamWriter`:
https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/0cc81b60eb184c92b8526348d4bb056ed563e9d6/src/vm/fastserializer.cpp#L31-L33

To make sure that the IPC response is the _first_ thing sent across the pipe, as there are several unbuffered writes that follow in the construction path of `EventPipeFile`.  This means that the IPC response will be sent _before_ `EventPipe::RunWithCallbackPostponed` has called the callbacks on the list of enabled providers and before `EventPipe::EnableInternal` has been called.

This do not pose an issue for most out-of-proc scenarios, however, this poses a bit of a race for in-proc scenarios.  If a process were to connect to itself, there is a window of time where you might be listening on the pipe, but not seeing events from requested providers, e.g.
```csharp
            var processId = Process.GetCurrentProcess().Id;
            var binaryReader = EventPipeClient.CollectTracing(processId, _sessionConfiguration, out var eventpipeSessionId);

            EventPipeEventSource source = null;
            var readerTask = new Task(() =>
            {
                source = new EventPipeEventSource(binaryReader);
                source.Dynamic.All += (eventData) =>
                {
                    // ...
                };
                source.Process();
            });

            readerTask.Start();
            _eventGeneratingAction();
            EventPipeClient.StopTracing(processId, eventpipeSessionId);
```
If `_eventGeneratingAction()` is sufficiently fast and this race occurs, you may not observe _any_ events from requested providers.

A possible solution to this, is to find every call to `IpcStream::Write` that might occur inside `EventPipe::Enable` and refactor them into methods that can be called later, e.g., `EventPipeFile::SendHeaderInformation()`, and to defer the creation of `EventPipeSession`'s flushing thread till later in `EventPipe::Enable`.  This would allow for a flow like this:

1. Diagnostics Server receives Collect Tracing command
2. Call `EventPipe::Enable`
3. Send IPC response
4. Send file format prerequisites
5. Turn on `EventPipeSession` flushing thread

This would ensure that `EventPipe::Enable` has finished turning on all the providers while still sending all the data in the correct order, i.e., IPC response, file format, events.

A fix to this should be non-breaking.

